f Canada after the failure of the Meech Lake Accord, and each of the others ponders various topics in the context of an era when the nature of the federation seems very much in questions. Authors from western Canada, the Atlantic region and Quebec explore the changing political landscapes in their areas, while others consider the shifting realities in aboriginal-state relations. Abortion, race relations, federal grants to interest groups, benefits to the elderly, and telecommunications policy are all reviewed as aspects of the "mature" agenda of the Progressive Conservative party in power. Taken as a group, these articles provide a multifaceted and sometimes surprising evaluation of government performance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGovernment spending policyzCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aAbele, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBickerton, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevine, Marina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoern, G. Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGagnon, Alain-G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibbins, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawkes, David C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPal, Leslie A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillips, Susan D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrince, Michael J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStasiulis, Daiva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTomlin, Brian W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu